    <div class="article-body">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>Provenance — thirty years in the desert, then full circle</h2>
        <p>
          The engine was rebuilt roughly thirty years ago and given about 10,000 break-in miles by its
          then-owner, who afterward parked the car and garaged it for the better part of thirty years in the
          eastern Washington desert. Rusty bought it out of that long-term storage and has since added fewer
          than 1,000 miles himself — this is a preserved car, kept garaged, not a daily driver.
        </p>
        <p>
          When it came out of storage, it went to Akers Porsche in Seattle for mechanical work. The shop
          owner, Denny Akers — since semi-retired — recognized the car: his own paperwork on file confirmed
          his shop had worked on it fifty years earlier. The 912 had gone full circle, back to its original
          "doctor."
        </p>
        <div class="callout">
          <b>In memory of Denny Akers:</b> Denny has since passed away. He was an important figure in the
          Pacific Northwest Porsche community, and Rusty considers himself fortunate to have had him as this
          car's mechanic — twice, fifty years apart.
        </div>
        <div class="callout auth">
          <b>On the record:</b> numbers-matching example — engine and transmission both confirmed matching —
          original wood-and-aluminum steering wheel (rare), factory-ordered 5-speed overdrive option, and a
          paper trail of service receipts spanning decades of Washington State ownership — this car has been
          in-state its whole life.
        </div>

        <h2>Provenance — the receipts</h2>
        <p>
          The paper trail is the backbone of this car's story: service records from Akers Porsche in
          Seattle, University Porsche/Audi and Wenatchee Volkswagen-Audi, and a car-audio receipt from its
          earlier ownership in Edmonds, WA — decades of documentation, all Washington State, that let a shop
          owner recognize his own fifty-year-old paperwork.
        </p>
